As Members of Congress, it’s our responsibility to conduct oversight. The public must see what’s happening inside these #border facilities.

The way our government is treating vulnerable men, women, & children goes against our values as a nation.

The overcrowding at the processing center in #McAllen was overwhelming.

Some have been here for WEEKS without the ability to bathe or brush their teeth.

The lights are on 24/7 and people are sleeping on concrete floors.

Some told us they have not had enough to eat. pic.twitter.com/4r817XMum0

Wrapping up our day after hearing heartbreaking stories of those seeking asylum at our border.

As our visit continues, my colleagues & I remain committed to providing oversight to take steps necessary to ensure no one suffers in our care. pic.twitter.com/fZLQJt3Fue
Children waiting in line for mats to sleep on at the #Ursula #detention center. pic.twitter.com/c3pUbldyXY
There are about 310 unaccompanied minors at this facility. pic.twitter.com/J3OlPx16KG
We met a young woman and her 10-month-old child at the #Ursula #detention center in McAllen. pic.twitter.com/MEpkBYANrR

Our first stop of the day was a Customs and Border Patrol station in McAllen, TX.

We saw overcrowding - 600 people in 12 cells.

Cement floors to sleep on.

This facility should only hold people for 72 hours.

Many had been there for 40-60 days. pic.twitter.com/ylBzUMIn1x

Just toured the holding facility in McAllen, TX.

What we have seen and heard so far has been troubling. https://twitter.com/RepSpeier/status/1150049076815237121 …

Returning to Texas w/ @RepSpeier, @RepFilemonVela, @RepGonzalez & colleagues to conduct oversight and see up close the conditions of #detention facilities holding vulnerable children & families.

I look forward to informing the public about what we see. https://kuster.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/kuster-to-travel-to-mcallen-and-brownsville-tx-to-observe-situation-at …
